node.text: After losing her brother and being severely injured in the Aug. 14 earthquake, 9-year-old Mia was overcome with grief. With her leg broken and her house destroyed, she has received psychological support from her local church, alongside Compassion. Mia is learning to find the strength and courage to face the future.

This week we are setting time aside to reflect. It has been one full year since COVID-19 became a global pandemic and caused widespread lockdowns. The impact of crises is never gender neutral, and COVID-19 is no exception. While everyone has been facing unprecedented challenges, women — especially mothers — have unique struggles. Meet Tribin, a mother of four in Bangladesh, and discover why the pandemic and all its challenges have made her believe in miracles.

#compassioninternational #covid_19 #womenshistorymonth

“I really believe that everybody has gifts and talents but for me, everything took me back to beauty and style. I believe that the project and the church gave me a place to take advantage of that talent and gift.”

“I do believe that God called me to do this and gives me the passion for it. I see myself in at least 5 years with my own house, my own business and being my own boss. I feel really proud when my son sees me as a hard working mama, as a super mama.” 

Sandy, Colombia 

#WomensHistoryMonth #CompassionAlumni

#WomensHistoryMonth #IWD2021 #CompassionAlumni

node.text: Meet Racquel, a 19-year-old in the Philippines who has always dreamed of becoming a doctor — regardless of the intense poverty surrounding her. node.text:
Meet Didier, a soccer coach in Mexico who refuses to let the pandemic make his players feel alone. Watch the full story on YouTube via link in bio!

For children to develop holistically, especially amid a crisis like the pandemic, they require physical, mental, emotional and spiritual care — and that’s exactly what Coach Didier is providing for each of the athletes he works with. Here at Compassion, we aim to empower all staff members and volunteers to find creative ways to provide diverse development opportunities. In Didier’s case, he used physical activity to help provide mental, emotional and spiritual support to teenagers when they needed it most. And this work couldn’t happen without the generous support of sponsors like you — thank you!

To watch the full video, visit the link in our bio.

Yoskiel’s parents were faced with the news nobody wants to hear: Your son has cancer. 

At age 3, Yoskiel was diagnosed with retinoblastoma (Stage 4) cancer. His family, farmers in rural Indonesia, didn't know how they would cover medical fees after the diagnosis. With the help of our local church partner in their community, Yoskiel received not only the medical assistance he needed, but also the financial support his parents needed.

After chemotherapy and surgery, Yoskiel is cancer free! #warriorwednesday

node.text:
Living with disabilities can be challenging for any young person and their family, but it can be even more difficult for a child or youth in poverty. Families often lack the resources for even the most basic medical interventions or needed supplies. Plus, the stigma of disabilities can leave these children feeling worthless and defeated.

These are just a few children with disabilities who have been empowered by Compassion's program.

After Nadia received a diagnosis of rheumatic heart disease, she was told that she would need medication, extra oxygen and regular health checkups. In Indonesia, usually only the rich receive this kind of care. Nadia's Compassion center was able to change that reality for her.

Wisdom was born prematurely with Down syndrome. Because of the round-the-clock care he needed, his mother couldn't work a job to meet his basic needs. A pastor whose church partners with Compassion was able to support, empower and care for the family.

Nelson was diagnosed with a form of muscular dystrophy. He often asked his mom why he had this disease and others didn't. Thankfully, Nelson was sponsored in Compassion's program at his local church and was able to get the care he needed!
